<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,330,1106]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
TYPE LOCALITY. Neighbourhood of 
<collectingRegion box="[564,666,473,498]" country="Iraq" name="Baghdad" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Baghdad</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[679,728,474,497]" name="Iraq" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Iraq</collectingCountry>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Rastegar-Pouyani, N." box="[740,1035,473,498]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="75 - 99" refId="ref62591" refString="Rastegar-Pouyani, N. (1999 a) Analysis of geographic variation in the Trapelus agilis complex. Zoology in the Middle East, 19, 75 - 99. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1080 / 09397140.1999.10637798" type="journal article" year="1999">Rastegar-Pouyani (1999a)</bibRefCitation>
designated the east-central regions of the central Iranian Plateau, about 
<quantity box="[579,667,509,534]" metricMagnitude="5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" unit="km" value="110.0">110 km</quantity>
SE of Esfahan city, as the ‘terra typica designata’ because, as he claimed, there have been no genuine records of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Olivier" baseAuthorityYear="1804" box="[683,774,545,570]" class="Reptilia" family="Agamidae" genus="Trapelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="agilis">
<emphasis box="[683,774,545,570]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">T. agilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[842,890,546,569]" name="Iraq" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Iraq</collectingCountry>
. But since the 
<typeStatus box="[1053,1151,546,570]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">syntypes</typeStatus>
are still extant and bear a precise locality that cannot be rejected or modified, 
<bibRefCitation author="Ananjeva, N. B. &amp; David, P. &amp; Barabanov, A. V. &amp; Dubois, A." box="[738,992,580,605]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="197 - 202" refId="ref44905" refString="Ananjeva, N. B., David, P., Barabanov, A. V. &amp; Dubois, A. (2013) On the type specimens of Trapelus ruderatus (Olivier, 1804) and some nomenclatural problems on Trapelus Cuvier, 1816 (Agamidae, Sauria). Russian Journal of Herpetology, 20, 197 - 202." type="journal article" year="2013">
Ananjeva 
<emphasis box="[853,910,580,605]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">et al.</emphasis>
(2013)
</bibRefCitation>
declared his designation as invalid and retained the original type as it appears in 
<bibRefCitation author="Olivier, G. A." box="[613,794,616,641]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" refId="ref61077" refString="Olivier, G. A. (1804) Atlas pour servir au voyage dans l'empire Othoman, L'Egypte et la Perse, fait par ordre du gouvernement, pendant les six premieres annees de la Republique. Deuxieme livraison. H. Agasse, Paris, 138 pp." type="book" year="1804">Olivier’s (1804)</bibRefCitation>
description.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,330,1106]" box="[151,1032,652,677]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
DISTRIBUTION. 
<collectingCountry box="[325,373,653,676]" name="Iraq" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Iraq</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[384,432,653,676]" name="Iran" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Iran</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[444,602,652,677]" name="Turkmenistan" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Turkmenistan</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[613,753,652,677]" name="Afghanistan" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Afghanistan</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[764,859,652,677]" name="Pakistan" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Pakistan</collectingCountry>
and NW 
<collectingCountry box="[967,1028,652,677]" name="India" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">India</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,330,1106]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
DISTRIBUTION IN 
<collectingCountry box="[356,412,688,711]" name="Iran" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">IRAN</collectingCountry>
. 
<figureCitation box="[430,516,687,712]" captionStart="FIGURES 20–25. 20" captionStartId="75.[151,264,1557,1580]" captionTargetBox="[171,1416,213,1516]" captionTargetId="figure-70@75.[151,1436,193,1536]" captionTargetPageId="75" captionText="FIGURES 20–25. 20. Trapelus agilis. Blue square denotes the type locality for T. a. khuzistanensis, dashed line delimits approximate boundary between this and the nominotypical subspecies. 21. Trapelus persicus. 22. Trapelus ruderatus. 23. Trapelus sanguinolentus. 24. Anguis colchica. 25. Pseudopus apodus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4929715" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4929715/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
. Across all Iran except the NW part of the Zagros. There are three recognized subspecies, two of which occur in Iran: the nominotypical one from most of Iran, SW Pakistan and Afghanistan; 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">T. a. khuzistanensis</emphasis>
from the Mesopotamian plain in SW Iran and adjoining areas; and 
<emphasis box="[1119,1331,759,784]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">T. a. pakistanensis</emphasis>
from SE Pakistan and NW India (
<bibRefCitation author="Rastegar-Pouyani, N." box="[426,705,795,820]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="75 - 99" refId="ref62591" refString="Rastegar-Pouyani, N. (1999 a) Analysis of geographic variation in the Trapelus agilis complex. Zoology in the Middle East, 19, 75 - 99. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1080 / 09397140.1999.10637798" type="journal article" year="1999">Rastegar-Pouyani 1999a</bibRefCitation>
, b).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,330,1106]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
HABITAT. Flat, open plains and semideserts of clay or gravel substrate with scattered shrubs or vegetation-covered mounds. Although not a vertical climber like 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1845" box="[679,785,866,891]" class="Reptilia" family="Agamidae" genus="Laudakia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[679,785,866,891]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Laudakia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, it climbs readily on shrubs, rocks and rock piles to use them as observation posts. Observed to retreat into shallow burrows.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,330,1106]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
REMARKS. 
<bibRefCitation author="Rastegar-Pouyani, N." box="[283,582,938,963]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="75 - 99" refId="ref62591" refString="Rastegar-Pouyani, N. (1999 a) Analysis of geographic variation in the Trapelus agilis complex. Zoology in the Middle East, 19, 75 - 99. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1080 / 09397140.1999.10637798" type="journal article" year="1999">Rastegar-Pouyani (1999a)</bibRefCitation>
synonymized 
<emphasis box="[758,914,938,963]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">T. a. isolepis</emphasis>
with 
<emphasis box="[990,1122,938,963]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
T. a. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Olivier" baseAuthorityYear="1804" box="[1060,1122,938,963]" class="Reptilia" family="Agamidae" genus="Trapelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="agilis">agilis</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
. The distribution of 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">T. a. khuzistanensis</emphasis>
is supposed to be restricted to 
<collectingRegion box="[672,790,973,998]" country="Iran" name="Khuzestan" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Khuzestan</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[849,1012,973,998]" country="Iran" name="Bushehr" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Bushehr Prov.</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Rastegar-Pouyani, N." box="[1027,1311,973,998]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="90 - 101" refId="ref62633" refString="Rastegar-Pouyani, N. (1999 b) Two New Subspecies of Trapelus agilis Complex (Sauria: Agamidae) From Lowland Southwestern Iran and Southeastern Pakistan. Asiatic Herpetological Research, 8, 90 - 101." type="journal article" year="1999">Rastegar-Pouyani 1999b</bibRefCitation>
), however, exact boundary between this and the nominotypical subspecies has not been studied in details yet.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
